# Steps to run the allocator test (assuming you are in the current folder)

1. Make sure the kernel images exist.
    ```bash
    ls -l build/tp/arch/x86/boot/bzImage
    # should return a file
    ls -l build/vanilla/arch/x86/boot/bzImage
    # should return a file

    # make sure you are in the correct group
    sudo usermod -aG kvm $USER
    newgrp kvm
    # this will affect other experiments because of group permissions
    # I suggest doing these experiments in a separate session
    # or pressing Ctrl+D after finishing the experiments to drop the new group permission

    id # you can use this command to check if you are in the kvm group

    ```

2. Run the TP script.
    ```bash
    NODE0_MEM=20G NODE1_MEM=10G ./run_thp_qemu.sh -k tp
    ```

    1. This will boot the TP kernel with 20GB memory on node0 and 10GB memory on node1. The entire TP pool is in node0.
    2. Inside the VM, run some verification commands to check the memory status:
        ```bash
        free -h
        # should have ~20GB free memory as 10GB is carved out by TP pool

        cat /proc/iceberg
        # should show something like this:
        # Utilization: 0/2600960
        # Huge pages available: 5080/5080
        # Fragmentation index: 0.000
        # ...
        ```
    3. go to experiment dir:
        ```bash
        cd /home/$USER/thp_alloc_exp/allocator_exp

        # may need to chmod +x the script
        ./thp_alloc.sh tp
        ```

